Preheat your oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9. Halve any large @cauliflower florets{300%g} and pop them onto a #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{}, @pepper{} and the @North Indian style spice mix{1%tsp}, then toss to coat. Spread them out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden brown and tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @korma curry paste{50%g} and garlic, cook for ~{1%minute}.

Add the @chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1%can}, chickpeas, @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, @sugar{1.5%tsp} and @water{300%ml} to the pan.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Bring to a boil, then lower the heat and simmer, stirring occasionally, until thickened, ~{10-12%minutes}.

While the soup simmers, cut each @plain naan{2} into 4 pieces and arrange on another baking tray.

When the cauliflower has ~{5%minutes} left, sprinkle the naans with a little water and pop into the oven to bake for ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the soup a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once the cauliflower has roasted, gently stir it through the soup.

Stir in the @butter{10%g} until fully melted. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Share the cauliflower soup between your #bowls{} and serve with the naan dippers on the side.

Swirl in some @low fat natural yoghurt{75%g} in each bowl to finish. Enjoy!